\begin_layout Standard
The
\series bold
 
\series default
basic goal of global optimization is to find the global minimum of a continuous multidimensional function and is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{*}=\mbox{arg}\min_{x\in S}f(x)\label{eq:eq1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\left[a_{1},b_{1}\right]\times\left[a_{2},b_{2}\right]\times\ldots\left[a_{n},b_{n}\right]
\]

\end_inset

with,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 representing lower and upper bounds for each variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In recent years,
 global optimization problems have become increasingly common in modern scientific fields,
 such as machine learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "machine_learning_1,machine_learning_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 big data analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "big data analysis"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 communication systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Communication Systems"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and energy management 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Energy Systems"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The increasing complexity of these applications leads to high-dimensional problems,
 making it particularly demanding to effectively explore the solution space of particular interest are Large-Scale Global Optimization (LSGO) problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DE_Large"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where the computational complexity increases significantly and classical deterministic methods often fail to find satisfactory solutions in reasonable time,
 either due to increased computational cost or due to trapping in local minima.
 The importance of LSGO problems was recognized internationally through competitions within the framework of the IEEE Congress on Evolutionary Computation (CEC) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Large1,Large2,Large3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which significantly strengthened research in this field.To address these challenges,
 there has been increasing interest in metaheuristic and stochastic algorithms that can efficiently approach the global optimum even in complex and high-dimensional environments.
 The Grey Wolf Optimizer (GWO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "GWO,GWO1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 is a widely used collective intelligence algorithm,
 inspired by the cooperative behavior of a wolf pack.
 Its simplicity of implementation and relatively fast convergence make it attractive for continuous optimization problems.
 However,
 in large-scale problems it exhibits limited exploration ability and an increased probability of premature convergence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this context,
 the Parallel Balanced Grey Wolf Optimizer (Parallel BGWO) is proposed,
 a parallel extension of GWO that aims to improve the balance between exploration and exploitation.
 The proposed algorithm divides the population into subpopulations that evolve simultaneously and exchange information,
 reducing the probability of being trapped at local extremes.
 In addition,
 a local optimization procedure is incorporated through the BFGS algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BFGS"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 while a termination rule 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stopping_rule"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 is implemented to effectively terminate the global optimization method.
 This modification avoids unnecessary calculations.
 Also,
 at the subpopulation level,
 different termination strategies (ANY,
 MAJORITY and ALL) are considered,
 which determine when the overall process is completed based on the convergence status of the individual clusters.
 The use of flexible termination criteria helps to avoid unnecessary calculations and improve the overall computational efficiency of the algorithm.
 The proposed algorithm was tested on real-world problems.
 As a representative real-world application,
 the training of Artificial Neural Networks (ANNs) can be formulated as a high-dimensional,
 non-convex optimization problem,
 where the objective is to determine the optimal set of model parameters by minimizing a predefined loss function.
 Due to the complexity of the search space and the presence of multiple local optima,
 conventional gradient-based methods may suffer from premature convergence.
 In this context,
 global optimization techniques provide a powerful alternative.
 For this reason,
 ANN training is employed in this work as an additional application to evaluate the effectiveness and robustness of the proposed Parallel BGWO algorithm.
\end_layout

