\begin_layout Standard
Global optimization problems constitute a fundamental research topic across many scientific domains,
 as the need to determine optimal solutions arises in an increasing number of applications.
 The growing complexity of modern systems often leads to high-dimensional problems,
 where classical deterministic methods frequently fail to provide reliable solutions.
 As a result,
 metaheuristic algorithms have emerged as an effective alternative for tackling complex optimization problems due to their ability to explore large search spaces and avoid local optima 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Genetic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Among the earliest and most widely used metaheuristic approaches are evolutionary algorithms,
 which simulate the principles of biological evolution.
 Genetic Algorithms (GA) were among the first successful global search techniques,
 relying on mechanisms such as selection,
 crossover,
 and mutation to evolve populations of candidate solutions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Genetic,Genetic-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Later,
 Differential Evolution (DE) was introduced as a powerful optimization algorithm for continuous problems,
 offering a simple structure and stable convergence behavior.
 Due to its robustness,
 DE has been widely applied in engineering optimization and energy management systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DE,DE1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Another important class of optimization methods is Swarm Intelligence algorithms,
 which are inspired by the collective behavior observed in natural systems.
 Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO) models the social interaction of particle swarms and has been successfully applied in global optimization and wireless communication problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "PSO,PSO-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Similarly,
 Ant Colony Optimization (ACO) simulates cooperative pathfinding
\series bold
 
\series default
behavior observed in ant colonies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ACO,ACO-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 while the Artificial Bee Colony (ABC) algorithm mimics the foraging behavior of honeybees and has been enhanced with learning mechanisms to improve its performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ABC,ABC-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Other bio-inspired optimization methods include the Firefly Algorithm (FA) and the Bat Algorithm (BA),
 which exploit attraction mechanisms and echolocation strategies respectively to achieve an efficient balance between exploration and exploitation in the search process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Firefly,Firefly_1,Bat,Bat_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In recent years,
 research has increasingly focused on the development of metaheuristic algorithms capable of improving search efficiency.
 Algorithms such as the Whale Optimization Algorithm (WOA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "woa,Woa1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Harris Hawks Optimization (HHO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hawks,Harris Hawks"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Aquila Optimizer (AO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aquila,Aquila_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Arithmetic Optimization Algorithm (AOA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "AOA,AOA_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 Magnificent Frigatebird Optimization Algorithm (MFO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MFO"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Salp Swarm Algorithm (SSA) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SSA,SSA_1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 attempt to enhance the balance between global exploration and local exploitation through adaptive search strategies.
 Among swarm-based optimization algorithms,
 the Grey Wolf Optimizer (GWO) has attracted considerable attention due to its simplicity and effectiveness in solving continuous optimization problems.
 Inspired by the leadership hierarchy and cooperative hunting behavior of grey wolves,
 GWO models the interaction between alpha,
 beta and delta wolves to guide the search process toward promising regions of the solution space 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "GWO,GWO1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Despite its effectiveness,
 the original GWO algorithm may suffer from premature convergence and reduced exploration ability when applied to large-scale or complex optimization problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address these limitations,
 several improved variants of the GWO algorithm have been proposed in recent years.
 Chen et al.
 introduced the Balanced Grey Wolf Optimizer (BGWO),
 which aims to maintain a better balance between exploration and exploitation during the optimization process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BGWO"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The proposed method was applied to optimize the weights of Backpropagation Neural Networks,
 improving the convergence behavior and predictive performance of the neural model.
 Similarly,
 Adhikary and Acharyya proposed the Randomized Balanced Grey Wolf Optimizer (RBGWO),
 a stochastic extension of BGWO that incorporates randomized mechanisms to enhance the diversity of the search process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BGWO1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This approach improves the ability of the algorithm to escape local optima and achieve better performance in real-world optimization problems.
 Furthermore,
 Wang et al.
 developed an Adaptively Balanced Grey Wolf Optimizer (ABGWO),
 which dynamically adjusts the balance between exploration and exploitation throughout the search process 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BGWO2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Their approach was applied to feature selection in high-dimensional classification problems,
 demonstrating improved classification accuracy while reducing data dimensionality.
 At the same time,
 recent studies emphasize the importance of parallel and collaborative metaheuristic strategies,
 where the population is divided into multiple subpopulations that explore different regions of the search space simultaneously.
 The exchange of information between these subpopulations helps improve diversity,
 reduce premature convergence,
 and accelerate the optimization process.
 Such collaborative approaches have been successfully demonstrated in modern parallel implementations of algorithms such as Smell Agent Optimization (SAO) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SAO,SAOP"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Overall,
 the evolution of metaheuristic optimization methods reflects a clear transition from classical evolutionary techniques toward hybrid,
 adaptive,
 and parallel optimization frameworks,
 capable of effectively addressing the challenges posed by complex large-scale optimization problems in modern applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address these limitations,
 parallel and cooperative optimization strategies have recently attracted increasing attention.
 By dividing the population into multiple interacting subpopulations,
 parallel approaches allow different regions of the search space to be explored simultaneously,
 improving diversity and reducing the probability of stagnation in local optima.
 Furthermore,
 hybridization with local optimization techniques can significantly improve convergence speed and solution accuracy.
 Motivated by these observations,
 this work proposes a Parallel Balanced Grey Wolf Optimizer (Parallel BGWO) designed to enhance the search efficiency of the classical GWO framework.
 The proposed method introduces a subpopulation-based parallel structure,
 where multiple groups of candidate solutions evolve simultaneously while exchanging information to maintain diversity.
 In addition,
 a local search mechanism based on the BFGS algorithm is incorporated to refine promising solutions and accelerate convergence.
 Also an adaptive termination rule is employed to avoid unnecessary computations when the algorithm approaches convergence.
 At the same time,
 flexible termination strategies (ANY,
 MAJORITY,
 ALL) are applied at the subpopulation level,
 which determine when the overall process is completed based on the convergence status of the individual clusters.
 The effectiveness of the proposed approach is evaluated through extensive experiments on benchmark optimization problems and real-world applications.
\end_layout

