\begin_layout Subsection

\series bold
The parallel algorithm of BGWO
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parallel implementation of the Balanced Grey Wolf Optimizer (BGWO) is based on dividing the population into 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 subpopulations,
 which are executed independently on different processing units.
 First,
 the parameters are initialized and the termination strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{S}$
\end_inset

 is selected.
 In each iteration,
 it is calculated how many subpopulations have satisfied the termination criterion.
 This information is compared with a threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

,
 which is determined by the 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{S}$
\end_inset

 strategy as follows:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ANY}$
\end_inset

 where the algorithm proceeds when at least one subpopulation terminates,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{MAJORITY}$
\end_inset

 where at least the majority of the subpopulations are required to have terminated and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{ALL}$
\end_inset

 where all subpopulations must have terminated.
 Then,
 each subpopulation evolves in parallel by performing the basic steps of BGWO (evaluation,
 leader selection,
 position update).
 At intervals,
 a propagation mechanism is applied to exchange good solutions between the subpopulations.
 The iteration counter is incremented and the overall termination criterion is checked.
 If it is not satisfied,
 the process is repeated.
 Upon termination,
 a local search is applied to the best solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{best}$
\end_inset

 and the final result is returned.
 The steps of Parallel BGWO algorithm are presented in the following Algorithm.
\end_layout

