\begin_layout Subsection

\series bold
The propagation mechanism
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:propagationMechanism"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During the propagation mechanism,
 the best values identified by each subpopulation are shared with the others,
 replacing their worst values.
 The goal of this process is to ensure that the subpopulations exchange their optimal findings,
 thereby enhancing the overall evolutionary process.
 The following four scenarios describe how propagation can take place:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
One-to-One(1to1):
 In this case,
 a randomly selected subpopulation sends its bests values to another subpopulation,
 also chosen at random.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
One-to-All(1toN):
 Here,
 a random subpopulation shares its bests values with all other subpopulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
All-to-One(Nto1):
 All subpopulations send their bests values to a single subpopulation,
 which is chosen at random.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
All-to-All(NtoN):
 Each subpopulation communicates its bests values to every other subpopulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This mechanism facilitates information exchange among subpopulations,
 increasing the likelihood of discovering optimal solutions through collaboration and communication.
\end_layout

