\begin_layout Subsection
Impact of the Number of Clusters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:4.3 Impact of the Number of Clusters"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 presents a comparative analysis of the number of objective function evaluations for a set of benchmark functions,
 in dimensions 25,
 50,
 100 and 150.
 The comparison is made in terms of the number of clusters used in the parallel or cooperative execution of the algorithm:
 1,
 3,
 10,
 20 and 30 clusters.
 The results show that when the population is divided into more clusters the number of required function calls is reduced,
 which means better computational efficiency.
 For example,
 in Büche Rastrigin_100 and Different Powers_100,
 where 1 cluster shows a higher computational cost of 17,769 and 23,887 respectively,
 in Büche Rastrigin_150 and Different Powers_150,
 it is 17,275 and 27,185 respectively.
 Therefore,
 the division of the population into subpopulations enhances diversity and promotes the parallel exploration of different regions of the search space,
 reducing premature convergence.
 It is also observed that 10 and 20 clusters tend to achieve the lowest or comparably low function calls values,
 for example for Büche Rastrigin_150 it is 6828 and 6837 respectively and for Different Powers_150 it is 12003 and 12858 respectively,
 which indicates a more effective balance between exploration and exploitation.
 On the contrary,
 further increase to 30 clusters does not lead to improvement and in several cases an increase in cost is observed.
 The total number of function calls decreases from 384,022 (1 cluster) to 363,819 (3 \SpecialChar allowbreak
\SpecialChar allowbreak
clusters),
 while a decrease is observed for 10–20 clusters (173,392- 174,401).
 On the contrary,
 in the case of 30 clusters,
 the total cost increases (228,652).
 In conclusion,
 the cooperative structure of multiple subpopulations can significantly reduce the computational cost.
\end_layout

