\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Discussion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results of this experimental study show that the proposed Parallel Balanced Grey Wolf Optimizer (ParallelBGWO) algorithm exhibits a clear improvement in terms of computational efficiency and stability of the optimization process,
 when compared with both the basic version of BGWO and other established metaheuristic algorithms.
 This improvement is systematically reflected in multiple aspects of the method,
 such as the number of objective function evaluations,
 the execution time,
 the effect of the number of subpopulations and the information propagation mechanism.
 One of the main findings of the study is that the introduction of multiple subpopulations substantially improves the performance of the algorithm.
 The comparison between different numbers of clusters showed that the transition from a single population to cooperating subpopulations significantly reduces the number of function calls and improves the overall behavior of the method.
 In particular,
 the configurations with 10 and 20 subpopulations.
 This result suggests that the appropriate distribution of the total population into subpopulations enhances diversity and improves the exploration of the search space.
 At the same time,
 the configuration with 30 subpopulations did not lead to further improvement,
 which indicates that excessive population fragmentation may limit the dynamics of each subpopulation and reduce the efficiency of the evolutionary process.
 The effect of the information dissemination mechanism (propagation) proved to be equally decisive.
 The comparison between the cases PROP = 0 and PROP = 1 showed that the activation of propagation leads to a drastic reduction in the number of evaluations of the objective function.
 This finding supports the view that information exchange between subpopulations is an important component for their effective cooperation and for faster guidance of the search towards high-quality solution areas.
 Of particular interest is the comparison of the 1to1,
 1toN,
 Nto1 and NtoN strategies.
 The NtoN strategy stood out as the most efficient choice,
 both in the case of 10 and in the case of 20 subpopulations.
 The choice of the subpopulation termination criterion also proved to be important,
 the ANY strategy consistently showed the smallest number of function calls,
 while MAJORITY and ALL showed higher computational costs.
 These results show that a more flexible termination rule can significantly reduce the computational load.
 The proposed method not only exhibited lower cost,
 but also greater stability,
 which is particularly important for high-dimensional optimization problems,
 where the reliability of the algorithm is as important as its average performance.
 Finally,
 the effectiveness of the proposed approach was further validated through Neural Network training experiments and practical real-world optimization problems,
 demonstrating its robustness and applicability in complex,
 high-dimensional,
 and non-convex search spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall,
 the present study shows that the success of ParallelBGWO is not due to a single mechanism,
 but to the combination of many interacting design choices:
 appropriate number of subpopulations,
 enabled information dissemination,
 fully bidirectional propagation strategy,
 and flexible termination rule.
 This synergistic structure allows for a better balance between exploration and exploitation,
 ultimately leading to significantly lower computational costs and greater stability.
 Despite the positive results,
 it would be interesting in the future to further investigate the behavior of the method in even higher dimensions and on more real-world problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Conclusions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study presented a parallel optimization framework based on the Parallel Balanced Gray Wolf Optimizer (ParallelBGWO),
 which aims to improve the efficiency and stability of the search process.
 Experimental evaluation showed that the proposed method achieves better performance in terms of computational cost and convergence behavior,
 compared to the basic version of BGWO and other metaheuristic methods.
 The results showed that splitting the population into multiple cooperating subpopulations significantly improves the optimization process.
 Specifically,
 the 10 and 20 cluster configurations offered the best balance between exploration and exploitation,
 leading to a significant reduction in the number of objective function evaluations.
 The information propagation mechanism also proved to be particularly important.
 Its activation led to a significant reduction in the number of objective function evaluations,
 confirming the importance of information exchange between subpopulations.
 Among the strategies examined,
 NtoN proved to be the most efficient,
 as it allows full information exchange between all clusters.
 Furthermore,
 the ANY termination criterion consistently presented a lower computational cost compared to MAJORITY and ALL.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall,
 the proposed ParallelBGWO framework is an efficient and stable optimization approach,
 combining multiple subpopulations,
 efficient information dissemination,
 and flexible termination criteria.
 Future research could consider the development of adaptive parameter tuning mechanisms,
 as well as the application of the method to real-world applications.
 Furthermore,
 an interesting direction is the hybridization of ParallelBGWO with other metaheuristic methods,
 such as Differential Evolution or Particle Swarm Optimization,
 with the aim of further improving the performance of the algorithm.
\end_layout

